Calculate yearly return series

Next, we convert prices to yearly return series with appropriate format.

Key is to use fortify.zoo(), which is used to convert a ‘zoo’ object into a dataframe that is suitable for plotting with ‘ggplot2’ or for manipulation with ‘dplyr’ functions.

# Calculate to return series
ret_yearly = prices %>%
  Return.calculate() %>%
  apply.yearly(., Return.cumulative) %>%
  round(4) %>%
  fortify.zoo() %>%
  mutate(Index = as.numeric(substring(Index, 1, 4)))

ret_yearly

Plot bar graph

Next, we plot it as a bar graph.

ggplot(ret_yearly, aes(x = Index, y = SPY.Close)) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = ret_yearly$Index,
                       expand = c(0.01, 0.01)) +
  geom_text(aes(label = paste(round(SPY.Close * 100, 2), "%"),
                vjust = ifelse(SPY.Close >= 0, -0.5, 1.5)),
            position = position_dodge(width = 1),
            size = 3) +
  xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL)

Breakdown of ggplot2 code

geom_bar(stat = 'identity'): - geom_bar() adds bar geometries to the plot. By default, geom_bar() creates a histogram, which counts values for each category of the x-axis. However, by setting stat = 'identity', it tells ggplot to use the y-values in the data as the bar heights directly. This is common when your y-values are already aggregated or calculated.

scale_x_continuous(breaks = ret_yearly$Index, expand = c(0.01, 0.01)): - breaks = ret_yearly$Index specifies where the ticks/markers on the x-axis should be placed. Here, it uses the Index values from ret_yearly as tick marks. - expand = c(0.01, 0.01) slightly expands the limits of the x-axis beyond the data to make the plot more visually appealing.

geom_text(aes(label = paste(round(SPY.Close * 100, 2), "%"), vjust = ifelse(SPY.Close >= 0, -0.5, 1.5)), position = position_dodge(width = 1), size = 3): - geom_text() adds text labels to the plot. - Inside aes(), label = paste(round(SPY.Close * 100, 2), "%") creates the label for each bar. SPY.Close is rounded to two decimal places, multiplied by 100 (converting it to a percentage), and concatenated with a “%” symbol. - vjust = ifelse(SPY.Close >= 0, -0.5, 1.5) vertically adjusts the position of the text. If SPY.Close is positive (the bar goes upwards), the text is placed slightly above the bar (-0.5), otherwise below the bar (1.5). - position = position_dodge(width = 1) is used to position the text in the case of dodged bar plots. Here, it might not change much as the bars are not dodged.

xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL): - xlab(NULL) and ylab(NULL) remove the x and y-axis labels, respectively.

Calculating Rolling Beta

Now we try to calcualte a rolling beta of six trading months (252 / 2 ~ 126).

We use the rollapply() function from the ‘zoo’ package.

# Define the rolling window size (days)
window_size <- 126

# Calculate rolling beta
rolling_beta <- rollapply(
  ret.2y,
  width = window_size,
  FUN = function(x) coef(lm(x[, 1] ~ x[, 2]))[2],
  by.column = FALSE,
  align = 'right'
)

# Create a time series object for plotting
rolling_beta_zoo <- zoo(rolling_beta, order.by = index(ret.2y))

# Plot the rolling beta
ggplot(data = fortify.zoo(rolling_beta_zoo), aes(x = Index, y = x)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = 'Rolling Beta of the Stock', x = 'Date', y = 'Rolling Beta')

Clearly, market beta is not static; we should be careful of using beta as an input for any financial models without accounting for the variability and stability of beta over time.

Low Vol Factor

There are three main points of why a low vol (beta) strategy achieves abnormal returns.

  1. Investors often have overconfidence in their capabilities, resulting in investing too much in high-volatility stocks. This has the effect of lowering expected returns of these high-vol stocks relative to low-vol stocks, making the low-vol strat favorable.

  2. Most institutional investors (pension funds, endowment funds, soverign funds, and mutual funds) cannot use leverage when investing. This implies that they would rather invest in high vol (beta) stocks than low vol (beta) stocks.

  3. High-vol stocks are more subject to volatility-drag, causing returns to diminish over long run.

next, we try to find the 30 lowest vol stock based on returns for past year.

First, I want to subset the data such that the new data frame only has the most recent year’s prices. There are many ways to achieve this, but I use ‘match-index’ method.

First, I convert the character values to date values using as.Date() function. Then, I would set the start and end dates that I want to subset the data frame by, and then use inequalities to subset the data frame. Below is

# Subset the data
KOR_price$X <- as.Date(KOR_price$X)

start_date <- KOR_price[nrow(KOR_price),1] - 365
end_date <- KOR_price[nrow(KOR_price),1]

date_idx <- which(end_date >= KOR_price$X &  KOR_price$X >= start_date)

KOR_price.y1 <- KOR_price[date_idx,]

# Calculate Returns
ret_y1 = KOR_price.y1 %>%
  Return.calculate()
# find standard deviations of all return series
apply(ret_y1, 2, sd) %>% head()

We see that NA values are returned. This is probably because NA values were produced from the process of calculating returns (after subsetting the data into one year worth price series).

# Handle NAs
na_col_idx <- which(colSums(is.na(ret_y1)) > 1)

Note that we multiply each element by \(\sqrt{252}\) to annualize the standard deviation calculated by daily returns. The reason why we multiply by the square root not 252 is because variance linearly scales, so we take the square root of the sum of random variables.

First, we take a look at the distribution of the standard deviation using a histogram.

# Plot sd as histogram
std_12m_daily %>% 
  data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = (`.`))) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  annotate("rect", xmin = -0.02, xmax = 0.02,
           ymin = 0,
           ymax = sum(std_12m_daily == 0, na.rm = TRUE) * 1.1,
           alpha=0.3, fill="red") +
  xlab(NULL)

Code Breakdown

  • The annotate() function adds a semi-transparent, red rectangle over the histogram with 0 standard deviation.

  • It is important to notice that the value aes(x=) parameter is (.). We must wrap . in backticks in order to successfully create a histogram representing distributions

Even after adjusting for stocks with not available prices in the most recent year, we see that many stocks have recorded a standard deviation of 0, meaning there was no change in price in this period.

This happens because there are stocks that have stopped trading, so price hasn’t changed for the past year.

There are a total of 36 stocks with 0 standard deviation.We exclude these stocks.

Caution

A word of caution. When excluding these stocks, you want to think about how to handle them. Do you want to remove them, or treat them as NA but still record those values. After some thought, one would realize the latter method is more convenient for future usage since the latter preserves the structure of the dataframe. That is, we could use the index derived from ranking the stds and subset the original dataset.

# Input NA for stocks with 0 std
std_12m_daily[std_12m_daily == 0] <- NA

# Check new plot
std_12m_daily %>% 
  data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = (`.`))) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  annotate("rect", xmin = -0.02, xmax = 0.02,

Finding low-vol portfolio using weekly returns

For consistency of results, we could go through the same process as above but this time using weekly returns.

Then we would look at the intersection of the two groups and select the common stocks to formulate a low-vol portfolio.

  apply(., 2, sd) %>%

Momentum Factor

We can think of momentum existing in two different ways:

  1. Earnings momentum

  2. Price momentum

We will select stocks to include in a price momentum portfolio based on the most recent 12 month returns.

We will use these files:

  1. KOR_price: consolidated price csv file
  2. KOR_tickers: xlsx file containing stock name, ticker, and etc

Momentum portfolio based on risk-adjusted 12m returns

Though we could use above stocks to form our long portfolio, note that we are completely ignoring volatility.

Thus, it would be make more sense to use the annualized standard deviation to find risk-adjusted performance and then form a ranked portfolio.

Then, we can look at intersections between the two groups to choose final components for our momentum portfolio.

Code Breakdown

  • gather(ticker, price, -Index) %>%: The gather() function is used to transform the data from a wide format to a long format. In the resulting dataframe, there will be columns named ticker, price, and Index. The ticker column contains what were originally column names, and price contains the corresponding values. The -Index indicates that the Index column (time/date) is to be preserved as is.

  • facet_wrap(. ~ ticker, scales = 'free'): Creates separate plots (facets) for each ticker, arranged in a grid. The scales = 'free' argument allows each facet to have its own y-axis scale, which is useful when the data range varies significantly across tickers.

  • xlab(NULL) and ylab(NULL): Removes labels from the x-axis and y-axis.

  • theme(...): Customizes the plot’s theme. Here, it’s used to remove the text from the x-axis (axis.text.x=element_blank()) and y-axis (axis.text.y=element_blank()).

A common element we see from the plot is that many of the stocks have shown exponential growth in price in the very last few months.

Value Factor

Value factors are one of the well-known factors, being promoted by famous value investors such as Benjamin Graham and Warren Buffett.

There are both risk-based explanations and behavior-based explanations.

Risk-based explanation

  • value stocks are priced low because of valid economic risks of the underlying companies. Thus, investors should be rewarded for holding stocks with a low potential.

Behavior-based explanation

  • value stocks are overlooked by investors and instead people tend to favor glamour stocks, or growth stocks. As a result, these glamour stocks are generally overpriced and value stocks underpriced, even if there is real chance of a turnaround.

Construct Value Portfolio based on PBR

The most widely used metric for constructing value portfolios is PBR. Moreover, research has uncovered that even though there are many value metrics out there, investing in PBR factor has shown performance similar to investing in other value factors.

For this section, we use the following csv files:

  1. ticker excel file
  2. Consolidated valuation csv file (contains PSR, PBR, PER values of all publicly listed stocks)

Construct Value Portfolio Using Multiple Value Ratios

While PBR is generally viewed as a robust value ratio, it is always good to use a mix of value ratios to enhance robustness of results.

Hence, our procedure is as follows:

  1. Rank transform the valuation matrix
  2. Find correlation of ranks for all four valuation ratios
  3. Use corrplot() function to generate a correlation diagram
  4. After confirming correlation is low, proceed to find stock rankings of aggregate sum of valuation rankings
  5. Pick top 30 stocks based on aggregate sum of rankings for each valuation ratio
# Import library
library(corrplot)
# Rank transform valuation matrix
rank_value = KOR_value %>% 
  mutate_all(list(~min_rank(.)))

cor(rank_value, use = 'complete.obs') %>%
  round(., 2) %>%
  corrplot(method = 'color', type = 'lower',
           addCoef.col = 'black', number.cex = 1,
           tl.cex = 1, tl.srt = 0, tl.col = 'black',
           col = colorRampPalette(
             c('blue', 'white', 'red'))(200),
           mar=c(0,0,0.5,0))

Code Breakdown

  • mutate_all() from the dplyr package is used to transform all columns in the dataframe. The transformation applied is min_rank(.), which ranks the data in each column (smaller numbers get lower ranks).
    • The result is stored in rank_value, which now contains the rank-transformed data.
  • cor(rank_value, use = 'complete.obs') calculates the correlation matrix for the rank_value dataframe. use = 'complete.obs' ensures that only complete cases (rows without any NA values) are used in the correlation calculation.
    • round(., 2) rounds the correlation values to two decimal places.
  • corrplot()
    • method = 'color' specifies that the correlations should be displayed using colored tiles.
    • type = 'lower' indicates that only the lower triangle of the correlation matrix should be displayed.
    • addCoef.col = 'black' sets the color of the correlation coefficients (numbers) added to the plot.
    • number.cex = 1 adjusts the size of the correlation coefficients.
    • tl.cex = 1 and tl.srt = 0 control the size and rotation of the text labels (tick labels) on the axes.
    • tl.col = 'black' sets the color of the text labels.
    • col = colorRampPalette(c('blue', 'white', 'red'))(200) defines a color palette ranging from blue (negative correlation) through white (no correlation) to red (positive correlation).
    • mar=c(0,0,0.5,0) sets the margins around the plot.

Understanding mutate_all() and list()

  • mutate_all() Function:

    • mutate_all() is used to apply a function or a set of transformations to every column in a dataframe. This is particularly useful when you want to perform the same operation across all columns.

  • Use of list():

    • In this context, list() is used to specify a set of functions or transformations to be applied. The syntax list(~function(.)) allows for a concise way to define the transformation using a formula interface. Here, the tilde ~ creates a formula, and the dot . is a placeholder for the column being processed.

  • Why Use list():

  • In dplyr version 1.0.0 and later, the use of list() in mutate_all() is recommended for defining transformations. It provides a cleaner, more standardized way to write code, especially when applying multiple functions.

  • The use of list() becomes more evident when applying multiple functions. For example, if you wanted to apply both min_rank() and another transformation (let’s say log1p), you could write it as mutate_all(list(~min_rank(.), ~log1p(.))).

  • The formula interface (~) inside list() is a tidyverse convention, providing a consistent way to define expressions applied to dataframe columns.

Hence, we can say that the use of list() in conjunction with mutate_all() provides a flexible and clear way to apply transformations across all columns of a dataframe, adhering to tidyverse syntax and enabling the easy extension to multiple functions if needed.

Notice that correlations between some of these ratios are close 0.5, lower than what one would expect from the same value factor. Hence, we proceed to select a new value portfolio considering all ranks.

Some nuance you could add is to give a weight to each valuation ratio; that is, you do not treat each valuation ratio equally. This is certainly a topic worthy of discussion, but we should also acknowledge that most often time, simple is the best. Hence, I expect using equally weighted rankings of each valuation ratio is good enough in practice as well.

Another important point is that there are a lot of NA values recorded, so we are essentially ignoring these stocks (negative earnings, cash flow, or just unavailable data). It should be taken into considerating when carrying out such strategy in practice.

Quality Factor

Quality is general compared to other fundamental factors; thus, we can have many forms of the factor. Below are some of the mainstream standards used to gauage quality of a company.

  1. Profitability
  2. Earnings stability
  3. Capital Structure
  4. Growth
  5. Accounting Quality
  6. Payout/Dilution (Dividends, Buyback etc)
  7. Investment (CAPEX, OPEX etc)

For this section, we will be importing the list that contains financial statements for all publicly listed stocks and the ticker file.

  1. RDS file containing financial statements of all publicly listed Korean companies (stored in the form of list)
  2. KOR_ticker (excel file containing stock info of all tickers)

Constructing Quality Portfolio Based on F - Score

The F-score is a measurement concocted by professor Piotroski in his paper from 2000. He argued that just investing in low PBR stocks is quite dangerous, so investors should screen for high quality stocks among the low PBR stocks.

Below is a summary of the F-score, which distinguishes financial quality into 3 criterion and a total of 9 measurements.

Category Metric Explanation
Profitability ROA 1 if ROA is positive
Profitability CFO 1 if CFO is positive
Profitability ΔROA 1 if ROA increased compared to the last year
Profitability ACCRUAL 1 if CFO > ROA
Financial Performance ΔLEVER 1 if Financial leverage decreased in the past year
Financial Performance ΔLIQUID 1 if Liquidity increased in the past year
Financial Performance EQ_OFFER 1 if No new equity offerings in the past year
Operating Efficiency ΔMARGIN 1 if Gross margin increased in the past year
Operating Efficiency ΔTURN 1 if Asset turnover increased in the past year

Basically, we can give a score of either 1 or 0 for each standard. Then we compute the sum of all F-indices and choose the stocks with a F-score of 9 to form the quality factor portfolio.

Before calculating the metric values, we must make sure that we are dividing by the numeric values. When naively performing KOR_fs$'당기순이익' / KOR_fs$'자산', we encounter an error since the first column of each element is a column containing character values.

Thus, we compute the division by specifying second to fourth columns, then append the ‘stock code’ column on the left.

# Profitability
ROA = (KOR_fs$'당기순이익'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자산'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

CFO = (KOR_fs$'영업활동으로인한현금흐름'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자산'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

ACCRUAL = (CFO[,2:4] - ROA[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

# Financial Performance
LEV = (KOR_fs$'장기차입금'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자산'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

LIQ = (KOR_fs$'유동자산'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'유동부채'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

OFFER = KOR_fs$'유상증자'

# Operating Efficiency
MARGIN = (KOR_fs$'매출총이익'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'매출액'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

TURN = (KOR_fs$'매출액'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자산'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything())

For ROA, we use net earnings and total assets.

For leverage, we use long-term debt and total assets.

For liquidity, we use current assets and current liabilities.

For OFFER, we use equity issuance.

For MARGIN, we use the gross profit margin.

For TURN, or turnover, we refer to asset turnover (revenue over total assets).

Now, we construct code that assesses either 1 or 0 for each index.

Note on data availability

If data is downloaded from January to April, there is a tendency for last year data to not include the full data. Thus, we must resort to data from 2 years ago. We make the assumption that the code is executed close to the data in which the data was downloaded. Thus, we use Sys.Date() function to calculate current date, extract the month and then form an if then statement to store the appropriate column index.

# Check whether month is one of 1, 2, 3, or 4

  if (lubridate::month(Sys.Date()) %in% c(1,2,3,4)) {
    col_num <- str_which(colnames(KOR_fs[[1]]), as.character(lubridate::year(Sys.Date()) - 2))
  } else {
    col_num <- str_which(colnames(KOR_fs[[1]]), as.character(lubridate::year(Sys.Date()) - 1))
  }

col_num
## [1] 4

The 4th column of each dataframe corresponds to the most recent year (last column).Now we proceed to calculate all the F-indices.

# Calculate F_1 through F_9
F_1 <- as.integer(ROA[, col_num] > 0)
F_2 <- as.integer(CFO[, col_num] > 0)
F_3 <- as.integer((ROA[, col_num] - ROA[, col_num - 1]) > 0)
F_4 <- as.integer(ACCRUAL[,col_num] > 0)
F_5 <- as.integer((LEV[, col_num] - LEV[, col_num - 1]) <= 0)
F_6 <- as.integer((LIQ[, col_num] - LIQ[, col_num - 1]) > 0)
F_7 = as.integer(is.na(OFFER[,col_num]) |
                   OFFER[,col_num] <= 0)
F_8 = as.integer(MARGIN[, col_num] -
                   MARGIN[, (col_num-1)] > 0)
F_9 = as.integer(TURN[,col_num] - TURN[,(col_num-1)] > 0)

# For F-score table
F_table <- cbind(F_1, F_2, F_3, F_4, F_5, F_6, F_7, F_8, F_9)
head(F_table)

Treatment of NA values An important subtlety to mention is that we ignore the NA values, since we cannot make any assumption of the value replacing NA (we do not know if quality score is low or high).

Next, we sum up across the rows, and then show a distribution plot that shows how stocks are distrbuted across the F-scores. If we use rowSums(), the inclusion of any NA value in a single row will result in the sum being NA. Instead, we use apply(., 1, na.rm = TRUE) to ignore NA values when taking the sum across the rows.

# Calculate F_score
F_score <- F_table %>%
  apply(., 1, sum, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
  setNames(KOR_ticker$`종목명`)

# Find distribution of stock F-scores
F_dist = prop.table(table(F_score)) %>% round(3)
# plot F-score distribution
F_dist %>%
  data.frame() %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = F_score, y = Freq,
             label = paste0(Freq * 100, '%'))) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity') +
  geom_text(color = 'black', size = 3, vjust = -0.4) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0, 0, 0.05),
                     labels = scales::percent) +
  ylab(NULL) +
  theme_classic()

Construct Portfolio Based on Ranking of Aggregate Quality Indices

This time, we aggregate rankings of ROE, Gross Profit, and Operating Cash Flow and choose stocks with the lowest rank sum.

# Import libraries
library(stringr)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(corrplot)
# Import files
KOR_fs <- readRDS("KOR_fs_clean.Rds")
KOR_ticker <- read.xlsx("KOR_ticker_2023-04-20.xlsx")
if (lubridate::month(Sys.Date()) %in% c(1,2,3,4) ) {
  num_col = str_which(colnames(KOR_fs[[1]]), as.character(lubridate::year(Sys.Date()) - 2))
} else {
  num_col = str_which(colnames(KOR_fs[[1]]), as.character(lubridate::year(Sys.Date()) - 1))
}

roe = ((KOR_fs$'당기순이익'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자본'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything()))[num_col]
gpa = ((KOR_fs$'매출총이익'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자산'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything()))[num_col]
cfo = ((KOR_fs$'영업활동으로인한현금흐름'[,2:4] / KOR_fs$'자산'[,2:4]) %>% mutate("stock code" = KOR_fs[[1]]$stockcode) %>% select("stock code", everything()))[num_col]

quality_profit =
  cbind(roe, gpa, cfo) %>%
  setNames(c('ROE', 'GPA', 'CFO'))

Since higher quality measurements are more desirable, we rank in a descending order.

rank_quality = quality_profit %>% 
  mutate_all(list(~min_rank(desc(.))))

cor(rank_quality, use = 'complete.obs') %>%
  round(., 2) %>%
  corrplot(method = 'color', type = 'lower',
           addCoef.col = 'black', number.cex = 1,
           tl.cex = 1, tl.srt = 0, tl.col = 'black',
           col =
             colorRampPalette(c('blue', 'white', 'red'))(200),
           mar=c(0,0,0.5,0))

Notice profitability indices have relatively low correlation with each other, so we can expect diversification effects by aggregating the rankings.

# Sum rank
rank_sum = rank_quality %>%
  rowSums()

invest_quality = rank(rank_sum) <= 30

KOR_ticker[invest_quality, ] %>%
  select('종목코드', '종목명', '시가총액', '업종명') %>%
  cbind(round(quality_profit[invest_quality, ], 4))
